{{for|the Mongolian district|Ongon, Sükhbaatar}}
{{Mongolian shamanism}}
'''Ongon''' (Mongolian; plural '''ongod''', Turkish: '''Ongun''', Azerbaijanese: '''Onqon''') is a type of spirit in the [[Mongolian shamanism|shamanistic belief system]] of [[Mongolia]].<ref>{{harvnb|Pedersen|2011|p=xii}}</ref> It is a common term in Turkish and Mongol mythologies. After death, all shamans become shamanic souls, ongod.<ref>{{harvnb|Pedersen|2011|p=166}}</ref> Idols can be consecrated to them within three years of the shaman's death and can be placed in the home ("home ongon") or in another locale, such as a shelter out in the open ("field ongon").<ref>{{harvnb|Shimamura|2004|p=546}}</ref> The ongon is also the physical representation of that spirit, made by a shaman, which plays a central part in the ritual that invokes the protection of the spirit.<ref>{{harvnb|Birtalan|2011|}}</ref> One well-known such spirit is [[Dayan Deerh]].<ref>{{harvnb|Birtalan|2011|p=26}}</ref>

The ongon is particularly important in [[black shamanism]]: the main function of the ''khar talynkh'' or black shaman is to bring people into contact with the ongon, whose spirit they call up "while drumming in a trance".<ref>{{harvnb|Shimamura|2004|p=651}}</ref> In late-nineteenth century Mongolia, according to Otgony Purev, [[yellow shamanism]] revered ongon as well, and every three years yellow shamans gathered in [[Dayan Deerh]] monastery in [[Khövsgöl Province]] to "renew" these ancestral spirits.<ref>{{harvnb|Shimamura|2004|p=650}}</ref>

==Physical representation==
Ongod are represented in the physical world in various ways. In the case of the [[Tuvans|Tuvan]] shamaness Yamaan, an ancestor spirit is represented in the handle of a drum, a carved figure with a pink head and chest, a black crown, and red eyes and forehead. A wire serves as arms, and on another wire ''holbogo'' are suspended to indicate the spirit's earring.<ref>{{harvnb|Pegg|2001|pp=127–28}}</ref> Some ongon live on in the place inhabited by the shaman: Agaaryn Khairhan, a mountain in [[Khövsgöl Province]], takes its name from one of the most powerful shamanesses of the [[Darkhad]] clan, Agaaryn Khairhan or Bagdan Udgan, who lived on the mountain in the eighteenth century.<ref>{{harvnb|Pegg|2001|p=121}}</ref> In present-day Northern Mongolia, specifically the [[Darkhad Valley]], clusters of ongod are found in transitional or liminal locations, such as the mouths of rivers or the borders between taiga and steppe:<ref>{{harvnb|Pedersen|2011|p=167}}</ref> In Darkhad Valley, the taiga and surrounding mountains are the traditional areas dominated by shamanism, where the steppe is dominated by Buddhism.<ref>{{harvnb|Pedersen|2011|p=13}}</ref>

Many Darkhad households own talismans, "lineage talismans" (''yazguur ongod'') or "household talismans" (''geriin ongod''), that both contain and attract spirits.<ref name=pederson158>{{harvnb|Pedersen|2011|p=158}}</ref>

